The paper discusses the use of variational autoencoders and Wasserstein autoencoders for collaborative filtering, which involves recommending items to users based on their past behavior. This topic is closely related to several sub-fields of computer science, including machine learning (cs.LG), information retrieval (cs.IR), artificial intelligence (cs.AI), computer vision (cs.CV), and social and information networks (cs.SI). However, since the paper focuses on the use of autoencoders for collaborative filtering, it is most likely to be classified under cs.LG, which is the primary sub-category for machine learning research.
